******
[2]
Date: Mon 4 Feb 2008
Source: The Telegraph, Calcutta, India [edited]
<http://www.telegraphindia.com/1080205/jsp/siliguri/story_8862993.jsp>


Animal diseases seem to be stalking Bengal with the district
administration [in Cooch Behar, West Bengal] announcing that the
anthrax bacteria was detected in cows that died in Mathabhanga
subdivision recently.

Cooch Behar district magistrate Rajesh Kumar Sinha said today [4 Feb
2008] that a family in Bhojanerchhara village, 34 km (21 mi) from
[Cooch Behar], lost 5 cows last Friday [1 Feb 2008]. "We had
collected the samples and sent them to the animal resource
development (ARD) laboratory in Cooch Behar for tests. The result was
positive for anthrax."

Sinha said another family in the same village had lost one cow to the
disease. At Jotpatki, in Mathabhanga, 7 more cows had died on 31 Jan
and 1 Feb [2008]. Samples of these animals, too, have been sent for
tests. "Given the situation, we have decided to vaccinate cattle in
the area from tomorrow," he added.

ARD [Animal Resources Department] sources said all the dead cows were
suffering from fever and died after bleeding from the mouth, typical
symptoms of cattle infected with the anthrax bacillus.

"The dead animals have been buried more than 8 ft (2.5 m)
underground," said Tapan Roy, the deputy director of the ARD in Cooch
Behar. Cows infected with anthrax bacteria do not survive for long
and stop giving milk. "There is no cause for panic, but care should
be taken not to eat contaminated beef," an official of the department said.

In June last year [2007], 2 persons died of anthrax in Murshidabad
after being admitted to the Infectious Diseases Hospital in Calcutta.
32 others were infected.

The North Dinajpur administration has imposed Section 144 in Itahar
block as the district gears up for a mop-up operation to search for
hidden poultry. The subdivisional officer of Raiganj, Asoke Kumar
Das, said this afternoon that the order issued yesterday [3 Feb 2008]
was for 56 villages. "We apprehend that there might be an attempt to
smuggle out poultry by people travelling in groups. So the assembly
of more than 5 persons has been prohibited," said Das. He said the
order has been conveyed to local panchayats [local assemblies] and
announced over the public address system.

