******
[3]
From: ProMEDmail.org
Date: Tue 5 Feb 2008
Source: Statesman News Service [edited]
<http://www.thestatesman.net/page.news.php?clid=10&theme=&usrsess=1&id=189215>


Vaccination drive has been started at Bhojaner-chhara village under
the Nishiganj-I gram panchayat in Mathabhanga-II block and the
adjoining areas to prevent the spread of anthrax among the cattle. A
massive awareness drive has been launched in these villages. The
villagers of the area have been asked not to consume the meat of dead
cows that have died of anthrax. They were also asked to bury dead
domestic cows. Removal of skins of the dead cows has also been discouraged.

Though a massive vaccination drive has been launched, not a single
case of anthrax infection among human beings has been reported till
now, the Cooch Behar DM, Mr Rajesh Kumar Sinha said.

The deaths of 6 cows on Friday night [1 Feb 2008] have made the
locals panicky about anthrax outbreak at Bhojaner-chhara village. On
being informed the ARD personnel had collected blood samples for
examination. As the samples tested positive for anthrax, it was
decided that cattle of the entire area would be vaccinated to stop
the disease from spreading.

The joint commissioner of the Union animal resources development
department, Dr S Negi, arrived [in Cooch Behar] this afternoon [5 Feb
2008] from New Delhi to review the situation that has arisen
following the outbreak of bird flu and anthrax. He would also
supervise the mop up drive, which is going on after the completion of
culling in the villages from where the avian flu cases have been
reported, according to the Cooch Behar ADM (D), Mr Pannalal
Mahapatra. The joint commissioner would visit all the bird flu
affected villages in Dinhata-I, Dinhata-II, and Mathabhanga-I blocks,
and also the anthrax-affected village in Mathabhanga-II block.

The quarantined members of the culling teams are becoming aggrieved.
Many of them have alleged that the administration has failed to
arrange for adequate food and other basic amenities for them. In this
cold it is hard to live somewhere else without proper blankets, they
said. When inquired about the allegation, Mr Mahapatra said that
arrangements have been made to hand over food tokens and better
bedding facilities from today [5 Feb 2008].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Reports out of West Bengal have varied somewhat in the numbers of
cattle affected but the most consistent are those posted. In spite of
the wording it appears that to date there have been no human cases.
The West Bengal authorities need to sit down and consider planning a
statewide regular vaccination of cattle. Reactive responses are both
very expensive and of limited effectiveness. The problem has been
going on for some time in the state. It should not be difficult to
delineate those areas with regular outbreaks needing immediate
action, and to set up a proper surveillance programme statewide to
look for and rapidly report unexpected livestock deaths so that they
can be promptly investigated. Latterly, numerous reports of suspected
cases indicate not only a sensitive public concern but also
uncertainty as to what is happening. They may also indicate a wider
distribution of this disease than is presently being diagnosed.

Other reports can be seen at
<http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20080040427&ch=2/5/2008%201:44:00%20PM>
and
<http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/anthrax-kills-cows-even-as-west-bengal-battles-bird-flu_10016402.html>.

Our thanks to Stadal Das, Angamuthu Kumar for these reports. - Mod.MHJ

The Indian province of West Bengal can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=22.9,79.6,5>. - CopyEd.MJ]
